For many young people, this felt like an attack on their freedom of expression and their way of connecting with the world.

What started as anger over the social media ban quickly grew into something bigger. Young Nepalis began voicing frustration over corruption, political favoritism, and the privileges enjoyed by the children of powerful leaders. Crowds of students and young workers gathered across cities, even defying curfews. Their chants and slogans called not only for the return of social media access but also for deeper changes in governance. The protests gained momentum and soon spread across the country, with people demanding more accountability and fairness from their leaders.

As the movement grew, the pressure on the government became impossible to ignore. Prime Minister K. P. Sharma Oli announced his resignation, and other officials followed.
